  "text": "One of the most basic distinctions made in job analysis has been the distinction between job-oriented and worker-oriented information [CITATION_1] . Job-oriented information typically includes job tasks and work procedures, whereas worker-oriented information is concerned with generalized worker requirements such as knowledge, skill, ability, and other worker characteristics (KSAOs) . Although there are obvious differences between these types of information, one key difference lies in the extent to which they are directly observable.",
  "correct_citation": {
